<ns2432:section xmlns:ns2432="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" xml:id="resources.information.technologies.java.j2ee.ejb.exceptions.applicationExceptions.applicationExceptions">

  <ns2433:title xmlns:ns2433="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Application Exceptions</ns2433:title>
  <ns2434:para xmlns:ns2434="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
    Application exceptions are those which the client should handle -- they communicate a
    problem with the business logic or the information supplied by the client.
  </ns2434:para>
  <ns2435:para xmlns:ns2435="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
    One can use any exception (other than <ns2436:literal xmlns:ns2436="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">java.lang.RuntimeException</ns2436:literal> which do
    not enforce the exception notification mechanism) for application exceptions. They are not
    wrapped by the container within <ns2437:literal xmlns:ns2437="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">RemoteException</ns2437:literal> and are serialized to the
    client -- all exceptions are serializable and hence they are copied to the client. The client
    side should handle all application exception.
  </ns2435:para>
</ns2432:section>